hat the call site class$ is at line 74, and any invocation should cover that. I need to create DocumentImpl for createDocument, but maybe that's not necessary. However, testing createDocument might hit another static Class.forName that isn't reported, so I might need a fixture from org.apache.xerces.dom.DocumentImpl. \\n\\nFocusing on this, I should just include getDocument. There should be a \\\"one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and generated test class files,\\\" but there’s currently no XML4JDOMAdapterTest. This helper isn't a top-level test class, which is something I need to be aware of. \\n\\nI wonder if there's a potential issue with package org.apache.xerces.parsers conflicting with JDK internal packages, as Java has com.sun.org.apache but not org.apache. I need to ensure the native image is reflective when invoking DOMParser methods. Since the stub is test code excluded from agent config, there might be a chance the native image sees Class.forName constants in JDOM. I might need to use getMethod on parserClass too. In the native image, I could use getMethod with constant method names and class arrays—this could potentially resolve things. But I'm also considering that Method.invoke will require proper metadata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining reflection analysis in GraalVM**\\n\\nI’m considering how GraalVM performs reflection analysis with constant patterns. It seems like using constructs like Class.forName(\\\"...\\\").getMethod(\\\"...\\\").invoke can be registered if the patterns are linear enough. I wonder if there are specific requirements to ensure this works correctly. Can I rely on this reflection method to function smoothly within the constraints of GraalVM? I’ll need to look into any limitations or best practices around this to ensure everything integrates properly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting method patterns**\\n\\nI'm looking into the method names and parameter classes, specifically focusing on the constants. It feels like the native image agent might miss something if it's not static. The existing Oracle adapter seems to follow the same pattern and passes successfully. I think it might be helpful to inspect the OracleV2 source to see if there's an analogous situation, especially since there's no setFeature mentioned there. Let’s see what I can uncover!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_MnsagDOrtFnkjPpk1O0PKQU0|fc_01aed8e892b2451d0169ef8e4482588197acd46c69d233a840", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"class OracleV|XMLParser|Class.forName\" /home/vjovanov/c/forge3/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/jdom/jdom/1.0/main/extracted/org/jdom/adapters -n && javap -classpath \"$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/jdom/jdom/1.0 -name 'jdom-1.0.jar' | head -1)\" -c -p org.jdom.adapters.OracleV1DOMAdapter | sed -n '1,190p'", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1278, "output": 712, "cacheRead": 26624, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 28614, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777307184697, "responseId": "resp_01aed8e892b2451d0169ef8e31de3481978b679cc683379fbf"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_MnsagDOrtFnkjPpk1O0PKQU0|fc_01aed8e892b2451d0169ef8e4482588197acd46c69d233a840", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge3/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/jdom/jdom/1.0/main/extracted/org/jdom/adapters/OracleV1DOMAdapter.java:73:public class OracleV1DOMAdapter extends AbstractDOMAdapter {\r\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge3/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/jdom/jdom/1.0/main/extracted/org/jdom/adapters/OracleV1DOMAdapter.java:94:            Class parserClass = Class.forName(\"oracle.xml.parser.XMLParser\");\r\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge3/metadata-forge/local_repositories/source_context/jd